 Identify Persistence Artifacts in Run/RunOnce Keys
Learning Objectives
By completing this lab, you will:

Analyze Windows registry files for persistence artifacts in Run/RunOnce keys
Use Registry Explorer to examine registry hives
Identify suspicious entries that indicate malware persistence
Understand common Windows persistence mechanisms
Prerequisites
Basic understanding of Windows registry structure
Familiarity with Linux command line
Knowledge of malware persistence concepts
Understanding of registry key paths and values
Lab Environment
Al Nafi provides Linux-based cloud machines for this lab. Click Start Lab to access your dedicated Linux machine. The provided machine is bare metal with no pre-installed tools, so you will install all required tools during the lab.

Task 1: Install Required Tools and Prepare Environment
Subtask 1.1: Install Wine and Dependencies
sudo apt update
sudo apt install -y wine winetricks wget unzip
Subtask 1.2: Configure Wine Environment
winecfg
Select Windows 10 from the dropdown and click OK.

Subtask 1.3: Download Registry Explorer
cd ~/
wget https://f001.backblazeb2.com/file/EricZimmermanTools/RegistryExplorer_RECmd.zip
unzip RegistryExplorer_RECmd.zip -d RegistryExplorer
Subtask 1.4: Create Sample Registry Files
Create a directory for sample registry files:

mkdir ~/registry_samples
cd ~/registry_samples
Download sample Windows registry hives:

# Create a mock SOFTWARE registry hive with persistence entries
cat > sample_software.reg << 'EOF'
Windows Registry Editor Version 5.00

[HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\SOFTWARE\Microsoft\Windows\CurrentVersion\Run]
"SecurityUpdate"="C:\\Windows\\System32\\svchost.exe -k netsvcs"
"WindowsDefender"="C:\\Program Files\\Windows Defender\\MSASCuiL.exe"
"MaliciousApp"="C:\\Users\\Public\\malware.exe"
"SystemCheck"="powershell.exe -WindowStyle Hidden -ExecutionPolicy Bypass -File C:\\temp\\check.ps1"

[HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\SOFTWARE\Microsoft\Windows\CurrentVersion\RunOnce]
"FirstRun"="C:\\Windows\\System32\\cmd.exe /c del C:\\temp\\installer.exe"
"SuspiciousOnce"="C:\\Users\\Public\\Downloads\\update.bat"

[HKEY_CURRENT_USER\SOFTWARE\Microsoft\Windows\CurrentVersion\Run]
"UserApp"="C:\\Users\\user\\AppData\\Roaming\\app.exe"
"BackdoorService"="rundll32.exe C:\\Windows\\System32\\malicious.dll,StartService"
EOF
Task 2: Use Registry Explorer to Locate Persistence Keys
Subtask 2.1: Launch Registry Explorer
cd ~/RegistryExplorer
wine RegistryExplorer.exe
Subtask 2.2: Load Registry File
In Registry Explorer, click File → Load Hive
Navigate to the sample registry file location
Select the sample_software.reg file
Click Open
Subtask 2.3: Navigate to Run Keys
Navigate to the following registry paths:

HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE persistence locations:

SOFTWARE\Microsoft\Windows\CurrentVersion\Run
SOFTWARE\Microsoft\Windows\CurrentVersion\RunOnce
HKEY_CURRENT_USER persistence locations:

SOFTWARE\Microsoft\Windows\CurrentVersion\Run
SOFTWARE\Microsoft\Windows\CurrentVersion\RunOnce
Subtask 2.4: Export Registry Data for Analysis
Create a script to extract Run key information:

cat > analyze_run_keys.sh << 'EOF'
#!/bin/bash

echo "=== Windows Registry Run Keys Analysis ==="
echo "Date: $(date)"
echo ""

echo "SUSPICIOUS INDICATORS TO LOOK FOR:"
echo "- Executables in unusual locations (temp, public folders)"
echo "- PowerShell commands with hidden windows"
echo "- Rundll32.exe with suspicious DLLs"
echo "- Base64 encoded commands"
echo "- Scripts in system directories"
echo ""

echo "=== HKLM\\SOFTWARE\\Microsoft\\Windows\\CurrentVersion\\Run ==="
grep -A 10 "CurrentVersion\\\\Run" ~/registry_samples/sample_software.reg | grep -E "^\".*\"="

echo ""
echo "=== HKLM\\SOFTWARE\\Microsoft\\Windows\\CurrentVersion\\RunOnce ==="
grep -A 10 "CurrentVersion\\\\RunOnce" ~/registry_samples/sample_software.reg | grep -E "^\".*\"="

echo ""
echo "=== Analysis Complete ==="
EOF

chmod +x analyze_run_keys.sh
./analyze_run_keys.sh
